# Module 04 — State & Memory

> Memory hierarchy + steering loop. Not "save everything" — save the right things at the right layer.

## Essence

The agent has three memory layers. Mix them and it gets stupid; keep them separate and it gets smart.

## Hard Constraints

### 1. Three layers, never mixed

| Layer | Lives in | Scope | Examples |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Working** | Current conversation | This task | Todo list, ephemeral plan, intermediate results |
| **Episodic** | `memory/*.md` | Cross-session facts | Preferences, project constraints, past corrections |
| **Procedural** | `.cursor/rules/*.mdc`, `AGENTS.md` | Skills, policies, conventions | How to run tests, how to commit, escalation rules |

Don't put a todo in memory. Don't put a preference in a rule. Don't put a policy in working memory.

### 2. MEMORY.md is an index

If you keep an index of memory entries:
- Main file < 200 lines (Cursor truncates after)
- Each entry is ONE line: `- [Title](file.md) — one-line hook`
- Details go in per-topic `.md` files
- Never inline memory content in the index

### 3. Don't write what git/code already says

**Bad memory entries:**
- "This project uses TypeScript" — derivable
- "The API lives in `api/`" — derivable
- "We fixed bug X on 2026-03-15" — that's commit history

**Good memory entries:**
- "User prefers pnpm over npm because of workspace issues with pnpm-lock.yaml format"
- "Don't touch `nuxt.config.ts` auto-imports — breaks IDE type inference"
- "When the user says 'finish that PR' they mean the draft one, not the newest"

### 4. Steering loop: writes must have triggers

User correction → write a feedback memory **immediately**. Include `Why:` and `How to apply:`:

```markdown
## Rule
Prefer framework error handling over try/catch.

**Why:** User corrected 2026-03-12. Manual try/catch hides Laravel's native exception middleware.

**How to apply:** In API controllers, throw and let the framework render. Only wrap when genuinely transforming the error.
```

Without `Why:`, the memory becomes a brittle rule that misfires in edge cases.

### 5. Memory expires

Before acting on a memory, verify the cited thing still exists:
- Memory says "X is at path Y" → check Y exists
- Memory says "function F handles Z" → grep for F
- Read a stale memory → update or delete, don't work around it

## When to apply

- User corrects you → write feedback memory with Why + How to apply
- Learning something non-obvious that persists across sessions → episodic layer
- About to repeat the same clarification for the third time → you missed saving a memory
- Memory says "the file is at X" → verify X exists before citing it

